scores = []
for C in c_vals:
    clf = LogisticRegression(C=C)
    clf.fit(x_train2, y_train)
    pred = clf.predict(x_test2) # Remember x_test2 is the out of sample data, we should not use it for training the model.
    scores.append(metrics.zero_one_loss(y_test, pred))

In [73]:

In [75]:
scores_tr = []
scores_val = []
for C in c_vals:
    clf = LogisticRegression(C=C)
    clf.fit(X_train_val, y_train_val)
    
    pred = clf.predict(X_train_val)
    scores_tr.append(metrics.zero_one_loss(y_train_val, pred))
    
    pred = clf.predict(X_val)
    scores_val.append(metrics.zero_one_loss(y_val, pred))
In [76]:
plt.plot(scores_tr, label='train')
plt.plot(scores_val, label='val')
plt.xticks(np.arange(len(c_vals)), c_vals, rotation=45)
plt.xlabel('C')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Grid Search¶

we are going to take a look at tuning several hyper parameters without any for loops in a blind grid search.

Hyper parameters are parameters that are not correctly learned by an estimator via the training data, they are passed as arguments to the constructor of the estimator classes.
